Metapawnien, which was given us by Maquaco· men, the king of Patuxent, is a certain storehouse os this mission, whence most os our bodily supplies are obtained. Father Philip Fisher lives in the princip-al town oi the colony, to which the narne of St. Mary’s is given. Father John Gravener lives in Kent Island, sixty miles distant. Father ’ Andrew White is distant still farther, one hundred and twenty miles, to wit: at Kittamaquindi, the metropolis of Pascatoe, having lived in the palaco with the king himself oi the place, whom they call Tayac, from the rnonth oi June, 1639.

The cause of the father's going there was on this wise. He had bestowed much time and labor for the conversion of the king of Patuxent, whichw indeed was expected by us all, both on account of the recollection of kindness received, for he had given to the society, as has been said, a , farm3 and because he was said to be very powerful among the barbarians, on account of his reputa· tion for wisdom and influence.
